Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] Capture Area
Kirk
If you are agreeing that adding the ferrite produces more signal
power, it's as much as we can expect :)  With the standard ferrite
rods in normal use, the losses are about right to produce the right
bandwidth without added losses.
Alan G3NOQ






On 29 October 2012 18:56, Kirk T McDonald <kirkmcd@princeton.edu> wrote:
> Alan B,
>
> One can indeed make comparisons whereby adding a ferrite to a loop antenn=
a increases the power captured =96 compared to some state of the system wit=
hout the antenna.
>
> It has been a struggle to identify what is that state to be used in such =
a comparison.
>
> I continue to find your comments about =93losses=94 and about Japanese en=
gineers distracting when trying to understand what should be compared with =
what to make the comparison look favorable for ferrites.
>
> Rather, Alan P=92s remarks seemed to be more to the point.
>
> A key is that a requirement for an AM radio is not only a sufficient sign=
al level, but a sufficient bandwidth to transmit an audio signal modulated =
onto the rf carrier.
>
> This requires lowering the Q of the system =96 to a rather low value comp=
ared to that which applies when the maximum power is captured.
>
> The Q is lowered by adding =93losses=94.    That is, =93losses=94 are not=
 to be avoided, but embraced as necessary for the function of the antenna a=
s an AM receiver.  [This is the Chu theorem in action.]
>
> These REQUIRED losses could be in the form of a load resistor, but ferrit=
e losses are a contribution to the losses.    But, even in the absence of f=
errite losses, and in the absence of intrinsic resistance of the coil, a lo=
ad resistor is needed to bring the system resistance up and the Q down, unt=
il the system bandwidth is as broad as required.
>
> For a particular coil, with and without the ferrite, the required system =
resistance to deliver a given bandwidth is actually the same with the ferri=
te or without.   So, in a sense, the needed =93losses=94 are the same with =
and without the ferrite.
>
> However, adding the ferrite increases the open-circuit voltage, as you li=
ke to say, so the extracted power,
> ~ Voc^2 / Rload
> goes up when the ferrite is added.
>
> [Voc^2 / Rrad stays the same with and without the ferrite, so the maximum=
 power that could be extracted stays the same.]
>
> -----------------
> A different question is whether the effect of the ferrite in increasing t=
he actual extracted power compared to the case of no ferrite =93matters=94.
>
> I think the answer to this is NO, in that what matters is the voltage inp=
ut to the voltage amplifier of the AM radio.   Adding the ferrite increase =
this voltage, which is what matters the most (and what the Japanese enginee=
rs were worried about, rather than about captured power, in my view).
>
> In the case of crystal radios, with no amplifier, captured power is more =
important, but ferrite loop antennas seem rare in this application.   That =
is, the story here has its separate complications.....
>
> ----------------
> -----------------
> ------------------
> What I have been discussing was quantified in my update (new sec. 4) to
> http://puhep1.princeton.edu/~mcdonald/examples/power.pdf
>
> I consider a loop of 100 turns or radius r ~ 1 cm, and length l ~ 1 cm, w=
ith and without a ferrite whose effective relative permeability is 100.
>
> A. Without the ferrite, Rrad ~ 1.5e-8 Ohms.
> If the wire resistance could be this low, so that this antenna were fully=
 "matched", the Qmax would be ~ 3e13, and the maximum power would be extrac=
ted from the wave.
>
> However, for use with an AM radio, we want the Q to be about 30. To get t=
his, the load resistance would have to be increased by a factor of Qmax/30 =
~ 1e12 to 1.5e4 Ohms, which reduces the extracted power by a factor of 1e-1=
2 compared to the maximum possible in principle.
>
> B. With the ferrite, Rrad ~ 1.5e-4 Ohms, and Qmax ~ 3e9.
> To operate with the desired Q ~ 30, the load resistance needs to be
> Rrad Qmax / 30 ~ 1.5e-4 x 1e8 =3D 1.5e4 Ohms =3D 15 kOhms (=3D same as in=
 case A).
> In this case, the extracted power is 1e-8 of the maximum possible.
>
> Comparing cases A and B, the extracted power is 1e4 times larger with the=
 ferrite (although only 1e-8 of the maximum possible) than without.
>
> So, we are agreed that adding the ferrite to a given loop antenna that is=
 loaded to have a fixed Q (of 30) with or without the load INCREASES the po=
wer captured from the incident wave.  In both cases the captured power is a=
 tiny fraction of the maximum possible power that could be captured, which =
is the same in both cases.
>
> --Kirk
